{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17610252","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17610252"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:58:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:58:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16148"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16148","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16148"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.53,0.03,0.29,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8839"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87423"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8839"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16148"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71642"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4340"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5372"},{"type":"tags","id":"8743"},{"type":"tags","id":"10087"},{"type":"tags","id":"10623"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21076"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21078"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/87423"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for preconception counselling. She is planning to start trying for pregnancy in the next few months. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is interested in learning about nutritional requirements during pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about nutrition in pregnancy is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Most pregnant women in Australia meet recommended daily intakes from core food groups","Folate requirements increase tenfold during pregnancy","Iodine requirements decrease during pregnancy","Iron requirements double during pregnancy","Vitamin C requirements remain unchanged during pregnancy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENutrition during pregnancy is crucial for both maternal and fetal health. Understanding the changes in nutritional requirements is essential for healthcare providers counselling women planning pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMost pregnant women in Australia meet recommended daily intakes\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Studies have shown that the majority of pregnant women in Australia do not meet the recommended daily intakes from the five core food groups, particularly for vegetables, lean meats, and dairy products.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFolate requirements increase tenfold\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Folate requirements increase by approximately 50% during pregnancy to support rapid cell division and growth. Folic acid supplementation of 500 microg daily is routinely recommended before conception and during early pregnancy to prevent neural tube defects, unless there is the presence of risk factors indicating a need for higher dosing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIodine requirements decrease\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Iodine requirements actually increase by about 50% during pregnancy to support fetal brain development and thyroid function. The recommended daily intake is 150 microg daily. Supplementation is often recommended in areas where iodine deficiency is common.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIron requirements double\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. Iron requirements increase significantly during pregnancy to support the expanding blood volume, placental development, and fetal growth. The recommended daily intake approximately doubles from 18 mg to 27 mg per day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin C requirements remain unchanged\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Vitamin C requirements increase during pregnancy to support immune function and iron absorption. The recommended daily intake increases from 45 mg to 60 mg per day.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Most pregnant women in Australia do not meet recommended daily intakes from the five core food groups.","Iron requirements double during pregnancy to support expanding blood volume, placental development, and fetal growth.","Folate requirements increase by 50% during pregnancy, with supplementation of 500 microg daily recommended preconception and during early pregnancy."],"references":["Malek L, Umberger W, Makrides M, Zhou SJ. Adherence to the Australian dietary guidelines during pregnancy: evidence from a national study. Public Health Nutr. 2016 May;19(7):1155-63. doi: 10.1017/S1368980015002232. Epub 2015 Jul 31. PMID: 26228526; PMCID: PMC10271122.","Soma-Pillay P, Nelson-Piercy C, Tolppanen H, Mebazaa A. Physiological changes in pregnancy. Cardiovasc J Afr. 2016 Mar-Apr;27(2):89-94. doi: 10.5830/CVJA-2016-021. PMID: 27213856; PMCID: PMC4928162","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71642"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16148"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71642"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-27T21:43:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T05:41:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8839"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87423"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4340"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Antenatal care","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-03T14:30:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-19T19:48:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"dat